{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"30f164ff-b999-44dd-98b5-3bdc5734037d","content":"\n\nRun **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's the difference:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. This is what you want after an SDK update, since workload manifests and packs may have changed.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs workloads that are already recorded but whose files are missing or corrupted. It doesn't fetch newer versions.\n\nAfter updating:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\ndotnet build\n```\n\nIf the build still fails, check `dotnet workload list` to confirm the `maui` workload is installed, and install it explicitly if needed:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload install maui\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"38d666c9-56ff-4e7b-b9d7-5e78918ce6d2","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":245},"id":"44f410dd-bdf8-42e4-8c6d-142e9dd53fd3","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:41:50.736Z","parentId":"37f55149-ec3d-44ac-85f0-faea50eebe95"}
